24. excidere: remove, eradicate. Cp. Cic. cle prov. consul. 18, 43, tristissimum tempus . . . era: animo . . . excidere. Surgical or medical metaphors are comparatively rare in Tacitus and else- where in Latin, except in Cicero, who had a peculiar fondness for them.

27. nihil, etc.: sc. ayere. Such ellipses of a verb of doing or acting, though not unusual, are particularly frequent in Tacitus. Cp. Introd. p. xxxi. publicae rei: public business. So again Germ. 13, 30. In this sense, the adjective must precede, because res pub- lica always has its restricted political meaning, but in other combina- tions with res in Tacitus, the attribute as a rule follows the noun. See Introd. p. xxvi.
